           	<td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">
                      <font face="arial" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Before I start I should mention that I use firewall, anti-virus, and anti-spyware software.  All of them are active ("always-on") protection, and I keep on top of patches with them.  I check for patches at least once a month, but usually more frequent than that.<br /><br />Furthermore, in so far as spyware, I have AdAware run a quick scan on the computer every time that it boots.<br /><br />Now for the point of my post.  Have any of you noticed any unusual computer activity while playing EQ?  Frequent and/or excessive hard disk churning (as your comp thinks like mad), or even weirder things such as your CD drive spinning up?<br /><br />The latter is what prompts me to post this.  I've frequently wondered if SoE/Varant/WhateverYouWantToCallThemNow are scanning my PC for whatever.  I do recall that quite some time ago they were doing exactly that.  Recording your temporary internet cache files and also prying into other areas of your computer.  They stopped that because they got caught, but it took someone with a packet sniffer and respectable computer know-how to catch them (it was the fellow behind grc.com if I remember correctly).<br /><br />I do not listen to audio CDs while playing EQ and I usually disable auto-protect in the anti-virus so that it doesn't cause problems while playing - sometimes I forget, but anyway..<br /><br />Last night while playing my system yet again went into serious think-fits.  The HDD was churning quite a bit for a minute or two before stopping.  Since you can now go into windowed mode I switched and watched for any programs executing or running which shouldn't be.  Nothing out of the ordinary. *shrug*<br /><br />This happens just about every time that I play EQ so I brushed it off.  What got me curious this time was the fact that the computer went into yet another (this time short) think-fit and then the CD spun up.  The CD does NOT need to spin up unless the lable on the disc is being read or, of course, its contents are being read.<br /><br />How many of you have experienced this, if any, or am I alone in this?  This is the first time that I've noticed the CD spin up.  Nothing was running in the background which would have fired up the CD.<br /><br />I don't want to sound too conspiratorial but I can't help but be curious.<br /><br />I have several gigs left on the 7200 RPM (I believe it is) hard drive that EQ is on and I'm using Win98 at the moment.  In a few weeks we'll be switching to a new system running WinXP and I'll see if the same thing happens then.  Until then, I'm mostly just curious to hear others experiences.<br /><br />It's at all possible that it's something else on my system which I haven't thought of, but the CD thing seemed just a little too strange to shrug off.  By the way, it spun up while I was in Kurn's Tower and had been there for a few hours.<br /><br />Anywho, bed time.  Good day folks.<br /><br />~Mysk<br /><br /><a href="http://www.myskyra.net/" target="_blank">http://www.myskyra.net/</a><br />-<br />The level 59 dyslexic Necromancer.</span id="msg"></font>
           	</td>
